display="inline"><![CDATA[f]]></fr:tex> is continuous at <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[x]]></fr:tex>. Let <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[(x_{n})]]></fr:tex> be a sequence in <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[X]]></fr:tex> that converges to <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[x]]></fr:tex>. Let <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\varepsilon >0]]></fr:tex>, we can choose a <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\delta >0]]></fr:tex> such that if <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[d(x,a)<\delta ]]></fr:tex> then <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\rho (f(x),f(a))<\varepsilon ]]></fr:tex>. Since <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[(x_{n})\to  x]]></fr:tex> converges, there is an index <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[N]]></fr:tex> such that for all <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[n\geq  N]]></fr:tex> we have <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[d(x,x_{n})<\delta ]]></fr:tex>. Then <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\rho (f(x),f(x_{n}))<\varepsilon ]]></fr:tex> for all <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[n\geq  N]]></fr:tex>. Hence <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[f(x_{n})\to  f(x)]]></fr:tex>.</fr:p>
<fr:p><fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[(\Longleftarrow )]]></fr:tex> Assume for any sequence <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[(x_{n})]]></fr:tex> in <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[X]]></fr:tex>, if <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[x_{n}\to  x]]></fr:tex>, then <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[f(x_{n})\to  f(x)]]></fr:tex> in <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[Y]]></fr:tex>. <fr:link
type="local"
href="nst-002J.xml"
addr="nst-002J"
title="Proof by contradiction">Proof by contradiction</fr:link>. Assume for contradiction that <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[f]]></fr:tex> is not continuous at <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[x]]></fr:tex>. That is, there is some <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\varepsilon _{0}>0]]></fr:tex> such that for every <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\delta >0]]></fr:tex>, there exists an <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[a\in  B_{\delta }(x)]]></fr:tex> such that <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\rho (f(x),f(a))\geq \varepsilon _{0}]]></fr:tex>. In particular, for each <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[n]]></fr:tex>, there exists a point <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[x_{n}\in  B_{1/n}(x)]]></fr:tex> such that <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\rho (f(x),f(x_{n}))\geq \varepsilon _{0}]]></fr:tex>. This defines a sequence <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[(x_{n})]]></fr:tex> in <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[X]]></fr:tex> that converges to <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[x]]></fr:tex> but whose image sequence <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[(f(x_{n}))]]></fr:tex> does not covnerge to <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[f(x)]]></fr:tex>. This contradicts our assumption, hence the result.</fr:p><html:span
xmlns:html="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml"
class="qed">∎</html:span></fr:mainmatter><fr:backmatter><fr:tree
